You are given an array A of length N. Find the number of pairs of (i, j) such that i &lt; j and A&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; + A&lt;sub&gt;j&lt;/sub&gt; = 2&lt;sup&gt;x&lt;/sup&gt; where x is an integer. Since the answer could be large return it modulo 10&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt; + 7.

##### Function description   

Complete the twiceMatch function in the editor below. It has the following parameter(s):  

Name |	Type |	Description
---|---|---  
A|	 INTEGER ARRAY | array of non-negative integers.

##### Return	

The function must return an INTEGER denoting the number of ordered pairs satisfying the condition.
Constraints

 - 1  ≤ N ≤  10&lt;sup&gt;5&lt;/sup&gt;
 - 1  ≤ A&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; ≤  10&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt;

##### Examples, first number in the input is the number of array values to follow

Input | Output | Output Description
---|---|---
4 1 15 2 7 | 2 | ordered pairs of indices satisfying the conditions are: (1, 2), (1, 4)
5 1 2 3 4 5 | 2 | ordered pairs of indices satisfying the conditions are: (1, 3), (3, 5)
5 2 2 2 2 2 | 10 | All pairs of (i, j) satisfies the condition.

Out of 15 Test cases only 1 is fails. The testcase is hidden.


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/DHI8B.png

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
import java.lang.Math;
public class Solution {
	public static int twiceMatch(int[] A) {
		int n = A.length;
		int mod = (int)(1e9 + 9);

		Map &lt;Integer, Integer&gt; freqMap = new HashMap &lt; &gt;();

		for (int num: A) {
			freqMap.put(num, freqMap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
		}

		int count = 0;

		for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
			for (int x = 0; x &lt;= 30; x++) {
				int target = (1 &lt;&lt; x) - A[i];
				if (target &lt; 0)
                    continue;

				if (freqMap.containsKey(target)) {
					int freq = freqMap.get(target);

					if (target == A[i]) {
						freq--;
					}

					count = (count + freq) % mod;
				}
			}
		}

		if (count % 2 != 0) {
			count--;
		}

		if (count &lt; 0) {
			count += mod;
		}

		if (count == 0) {
			return - 1;
		}

		return count / 2;
	}
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner scan = new Scanner(System. in );
		int N;
		N = scan.nextInt();
		int[] A = new int[N];
		for (int j = 0; j &lt; N; j++) {
			A[j] = scan.nextInt();
		}
		int result;
		result = twiceMatch(A);
		System.out.print(result);
		return;
	}
}
